<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="590" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[131,776,410,699]" pageId="29" pageNumber="590">DIAGNOSIS. — Bifoliate lenticular, branched colonies. Branch transverse section lens-shaped. Autozooecia short, tubular, recumbent at their bases in endozone, bending sharply to colony surface, rectangular to subrhomboidal at their bases, becoming oval at branch surface, arranged in 8 to 15 regular alternating rows on branches. Hemisepta absent. Basal diaphragms rare to common. Mesotheca straight to weakly undulating, two-layered, without median rods. Autozooecial walls granular, in endozone; thick, finely laminated in exozone. Paurostyles in the laminated skeleton abundant, arranged in up to 5 rows between autozooecial apertures, rounded to weakly stellate in tangential section. Maculae absent.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
